WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:05.160
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington, DC.

00:00:16.350 --> 00:00:17.860
&gt;&gt; Al Banks: So my
name is Al Banks,

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:21.080
and I'm the Chief Operating
Officer for Library Services

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:24.270
and so I'd like to welcome you
to the Library of Congress.

00:00:24.270 --> 00:00:27.620
On behalf of the Librarian
of Congress, Dr. Carla Hayden

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:30.650
and our entire team, I'd like
to welcome you and thank you

00:00:30.650 --> 00:00:36.580
for choosing to today's Gold
Star Legacy Panel Discussion.

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:39.810
The Veterans History Project is
one of the most popular projects

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:42.540
at the Library of
Congress, and is considered

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:46.170
on of the largest oral history
projects in the country.

00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:48.480
Through a Congressional
Mandate to collect,

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:50.870
preserve and make accessible.

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:54.230
The memories of our nation's
veterans we hear directly

00:00:54.230 --> 00:00:59.290
from them what they
saw, felt and heard.

00:00:59.290 --> 00:01:02.540
The human experience
of military service.

00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:05.990
These first hand narratives
reinforced the realities

00:01:05.990 --> 00:01:07.700
of their selfless service

00:01:07.700 --> 00:01:12.860
so that we all better
understand and appreciate them.

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:14.740
When the Gold Star
Families Voices Act

00:01:14.740 --> 00:01:19.430
of 2016 amended the Veterans
History Project legislation its

00:01:19.430 --> 00:01:22.870
scope expanded to
include oral histories

00:01:22.870 --> 00:01:25.800
from immediate family
members of the armed forces

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:29.370
who became missing in action
or who died as a result

00:01:29.370 --> 00:01:32.580
of their wartime service.

00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:36.460
This revision reinforces our
dedication to making sure

00:01:36.460 --> 00:01:39.510
that all military
veterans are not forgotten,

00:01:39.510 --> 00:01:44.380
but instead are heard,
appreciated and remembered

00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:48.420
with a lasting, living legacy.

00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:51.290
Through our work with the
Gold Start individuals

00:01:51.290 --> 00:01:55.740
and organizations, some
of whom are here today,

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:57.950
we are able to demonstrate
to these families

00:01:57.950 --> 00:02:02.270
and the American people that
the legacy of these heroes is

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:06.210
in the memory of
a grateful nation.

00:02:06.210 --> 00:02:10.470
This Sunday marks Gold Star
Mothers and Families Day

00:02:10.470 --> 00:02:13.050
which is observed in the
US on the last Sunday

00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:15.530
of September each year.

00:02:15.530 --> 00:02:17.480
We are pleased to
commemorate this day

00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:20.150
with this landmark
panel discussion.

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:23.990
In a few moments you will
hear from the leaders

00:02:23.990 --> 00:02:27.050
of Gold Star organizations
and individuals

00:02:27.050 --> 00:02:30.430
who will explore ways that
families, organizations

00:02:30.430 --> 00:02:33.500
and communities are
currently working to honor

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:37.130
and preserve the legacy
of our fallen members

00:02:37.130 --> 00:02:39.360
of our service members.

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:40.780
They will also highlight ways

00:02:40.780 --> 00:02:44.700
in which we all can support
families of the fallen,

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:48.940
and ensure their loved ones
are honored and remember,

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:51.320
and remembered in
a suitable way.

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:53.890
At this time, I'm delighted

00:02:53.890 --> 00:02:59.550
to introduce today's Gold
Star Legacy panel moderator.

00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:04.710
Emmy Award Winning News
Correspondent Mr. Mort Dean.

00:03:04.710 --> 00:03:09.740
As a correspondent of CBS News
20 years ago, and with ABC

00:03:09.740 --> 00:03:13.120
for 14 years, his many
assignments includes the US

00:03:13.120 --> 00:03:18.850
space program, political
campaigns and the Vietnam War.

00:03:18.850 --> 00:03:22.600
Putting himself in harm's
way, Mr. Dean reported

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:26.200
on the invasion of Grenada,
the [inaudible] War,

00:03:26.200 --> 00:03:27.810
and Cuba from the early days

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:31.580
of the Castro regime
through the present.

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:34.210
He reported on Iran
when the hostage crisis

00:03:34.210 --> 00:03:37.400
from Somalia during
the US intervention,

00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:40.800
the turmoil in Israel and
the Palestinian territory

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:45.440
and the military action in
Kosovo involving US marines.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:52.000
He covered Saddam Hussain's
Iraq, the NATO air attacks

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.500
in Belgrade, the terror attack
on the USS Cole in Yemen,

00:03:56.500 --> 00:04:02.090
the bombing of the US embassy in
Nairobi, and the US retaliation

00:04:02.090 --> 00:04:05.130
in Sudan as well as the first
terrorist terrorists attacks

00:04:05.130 --> 00:04:07.960
on the World Trade
Center in 1993.

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:13.170
With his more recent endeavors,
Mr. Dean has written, directed

00:04:13.170 --> 00:04:17.910
and produced a PBS
documentary, American Medivac.

00:04:17.910 --> 00:04:21.650
The documentary tells the story
of a harrowing medivac mission

00:04:21.650 --> 00:04:27.530
to rescue three wounded soldiers
from enemy fire in a rice patty.

00:04:27.530 --> 00:04:32.310
Mr. Dean long wondered what
had become of the medivac troop

00:04:32.310 --> 00:04:34.260
and the bloody men
who were airlifted

00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:37.940
to safety on that day in 1971.

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:39.950
American Medivac is a story

00:04:39.950 --> 00:04:43.630
of their reunion more
than 40 years later.

00:04:43.630 --> 00:04:48.510
It is my pleasure to welcome
and introduce Mr. Mort Dean.

00:04:48.510 --> 00:04:57.440
[ Applause ]

00:04:57.440 --> 00:05:00.130
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: That was so long,
that introduction that you,

00:05:00.130 --> 00:05:03.260
you probably think I wrote
it, but I had nothing to do,

00:05:03.260 --> 00:05:07.610
to do with is, and I have to
say given the current attitude

00:05:07.610 --> 00:05:11.400
in among some people,
including the Commander in Chief

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:15.360
about reporters, I think
it's very gutsy of you all

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:16.660
to have me here today.

00:05:16.660 --> 00:05:20.380
And, and if any of you
are still on active duty,

00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:24.290
I wonder what this is going to
mean to you and your future.

00:05:24.290 --> 00:05:28.370
I'm very honored to be here
and to be in your company

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:32.350
and thank you Library
of Congress for caring

00:05:32.350 --> 00:05:36.080
about America, for caring
about Gold Star families,

00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:41.070
and thank you New Day USA for
caring about America and caring

00:05:41.070 --> 00:05:43.410
about Gold Star families.

00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:47.880
Anyone who knows a Gold
Star family is well aware

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:50.870
that Gold Star mothers
and fathers and brothers

00:05:50.870 --> 00:05:55.590
and sisters, Gold Star
families often wear a gold star,

00:05:55.590 --> 00:05:59.200
but they also carry a
gold star in their hearts.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:03.440
And I believe it's the duty
of all Americans to reach

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:07.580
into those hearts, to
touch those gold stars,

00:06:07.580 --> 00:06:11.710
to embrace them with
our love and respect.

00:06:11.710 --> 00:06:14.340
And to polish them
up a little bit

00:06:14.340 --> 00:06:17.680
and make them a little
less burdensome to carry.

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:20.960
And show that we too,
the civilians care.

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:25.170
That we too will
never, ever forget.

00:06:25.170 --> 00:06:29.240
That's why I'm here and that's
why New Day USA is here,

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:32.800
and has brought many
of us together today.

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:37.930
It's why others of you are
here also to say to those

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:40.880
who carry a gold
star in their hearts

00:06:40.880 --> 00:06:46.070
that you are not alone today,
and you will never be alone,

00:06:46.070 --> 00:06:50.120
and America truly
cares about you.

00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:52.420
We're going to hear more
about that from our panel

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:54.350
in just a moment
about what the they

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:58.520
and their organizations are
doing for Gold Star families

00:06:58.520 --> 00:07:02.290
and what we and our
government needs to do.

00:07:02.290 --> 00:07:05.600
I was at an event, a meeting
in Washington just a couple

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:09.390
of weeks ago, and the
discussion did get

00:07:09.390 --> 00:07:11.580
around to Gold Star families.

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:15.370
It was a meeting of the Vietnam
War Commemoration Commission,

00:07:15.370 --> 00:07:17.080
Steering Committee.

00:07:17.080 --> 00:07:20.330
And we were talking about
Gold Stars and families

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:22.640
and the activities
that are taking place

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:24.840
in Washington this
coming weekend.

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:28.260
And an old soldier, a
former, a current medal

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:31.640
of honor recipient
said that he was

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:33.860
in a gold star family
event just a couple

00:07:33.860 --> 00:07:35.470
of years ago here in Washington.

00:07:35.470 --> 00:07:38.670
And he raised the question,
he said how many members

00:07:38.670 --> 00:07:40.660
of Congress are out there?

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:42.510
Nobody. How many members

00:07:42.510 --> 00:07:46.280
of a Congressional
office are out there?

00:07:46.280 --> 00:07:49.870
Nobody. And he turned to the
crowd the other day and said,

00:07:49.870 --> 00:07:54.100
this is one of the jobs we
have to do to convince people

00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:57.780
in the highest offices of our
country that there are people

00:07:57.780 --> 00:08:00.970
out there who deserve
the government's care

00:08:00.970 --> 00:08:03.600
and respect and honor.

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:08.010
So let me introduce the people
on the panel, Jenine Melton,

00:08:08.010 --> 00:08:14.890
US Army Veteran, two tours in
Iraq and a Gold Star sister.

00:08:14.890 --> 00:08:18.840
What does the term
Gold Star mean to you?

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:20.850
&gt;&gt; Jenine Melton: When I
think of the term Gold Star,

00:08:20.850 --> 00:08:25.390
to me it symbolizes sacrifice,
the ultimate sacrifice

00:08:25.390 --> 00:08:29.060
that our fallen heroes made
to preserve our freedom.

00:08:29.060 --> 00:08:32.920
So every time I look at the
gold star, it reminds me

00:08:32.920 --> 00:08:35.200
that freedom is not free.

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:40.010
There is a fallen hero that
made the ultimate sacrifice,

00:08:40.010 --> 00:08:42.720
and then there is a
family that's associated

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:44.320
with every single star.

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:48.270
So when you see the service
flag hanging in a window,

00:08:48.270 --> 00:08:50.240
or a magnet on the back

00:08:50.240 --> 00:08:53.700
of somebody's car there's
a story behind every star,

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:58.710
a story of pain, a story of
sacrifice and a story ultimately

00:08:58.710 --> 00:09:02.100
of love and we should
never forget that.

00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:06.020
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Yeah my
understanding is what I said is

00:09:06.020 --> 00:09:08.910
that when you mentioned
Gold Star to,

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:13.550
to many people they don't know
what you're talking about,

00:09:13.550 --> 00:09:17.480
it's not the way it was
when I was a kid growing up,

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:20.370
just after World War
II when you would go

00:09:20.370 --> 00:09:22.790
through the neighborhood
and see gold stars hanging

00:09:22.790 --> 00:09:25.150
in the windows of
so many families.

00:09:25.150 --> 00:09:26.670
Have you found that true?

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:28.250
&gt;&gt; Jenine Melton: Yes
I was actually amazed.

00:09:28.250 --> 00:09:32.500
Coming from active duty, prior
to the passing of my brother,

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:35.460
I did not know and there
were actually some chaplains

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:37.800
that I had met when
I was on active duty

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:39.340
and separated that did not know.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:42.590
So right now, and I find it
to be my personal mission

00:09:42.590 --> 00:09:44.530
to make people aware of that.

00:09:44.530 --> 00:09:47.640
To let them know about the
sacrifice associated with that.

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:49.610
Even currently I'm a
civil servant working

00:09:49.610 --> 00:09:51.170
with the Department
of Veteran Affairs

00:09:51.170 --> 00:09:53.900
and they've been really trying
to do more with initiatives

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:57.130
with veterans and even talking
about Gold Star families,

00:09:57.130 --> 00:09:59.160
but really a lot of
people do not know,

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:01.640
which is why I'm glad we
have platforms like this

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:04.120
to promote awareness
and make people aware

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:07.310
of our family sacrifices
and our heroes.

00:10:08.360 --> 00:10:10.310
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Becky
Christmas is President

00:10:10.310 --> 00:10:14.420
of the American Gold
Star Mothers, Inc.

00:10:14.420 --> 00:10:18.750
And I read something about
when you were named president,

00:10:18.750 --> 00:10:21.920
and you said in your,
your thank you speech,

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:24.520
we are mothers on a mission.

00:10:24.520 --> 00:10:26.980
What is your mission?

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:30.030
&gt;&gt; Becky Christmas: The mission
of American Gold Star Mothers,

00:10:30.030 --> 00:10:33.740
Incorporated, is to serve
and support veterans

00:10:33.740 --> 00:10:37.590
and the families of the fallen
and our active military.

00:10:37.590 --> 00:10:42.580
We are a veteran service
organization, 90 years old.

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:45.860
It was started in 1928
by a Gold Star mother

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:48.750
who lost her son in World War I.

00:10:48.750 --> 00:10:50.050
And that is our mission.

00:10:50.050 --> 00:10:55.070
And so our theme this year
is Mothers On A Mission,

00:10:55.070 --> 00:10:58.030
A Powerful Force,
because we do have a voice

00:10:58.030 --> 00:10:59.820
that people will listen to.

00:10:59.820 --> 00:11:02.960
And it's important, because
we can speak for some

00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:07.660
of our veterans that aren't able
to, and some of our families

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:10.790
that aren't able to, and
that is, that is what we do

00:11:10.790 --> 00:11:16.050
to take our grief, serve in a
positive way, because grief held

00:11:16.050 --> 00:11:17.930
within can be destructive.

00:11:17.930 --> 00:11:21.910
So we learned that and we feel
that service is our mission.

00:11:21.910 --> 00:11:24.350
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: And Becky
you really know what you're

00:11:24.350 --> 00:11:25.650
talking about.

00:11:25.650 --> 00:11:27.330
Your son served in Iraq.

00:11:27.330 --> 00:11:28.630
&gt;&gt; Becky Christmas: Yes.

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:29.930
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Tell us about him.

00:11:29.930 --> 00:11:32.320
&gt;&gt; Becky Christmas: My son
was Captain Todd Christmas.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:35.070
Todd was very proud
to serve in the army.

00:11:35.070 --> 00:11:37.400
That was all he ever
wanted to do.

00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:40.130
And he hoped to have
a long career.

00:11:40.130 --> 00:11:44.070
He was deployed to Iraq in 2003,

00:11:44.070 --> 00:11:48.680
and he was the recipient
of a bronze star.

00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:50.890
He was a ranch boy
from New Mexico

00:11:50.890 --> 00:11:54.110
who could be quite
innovative with things

00:11:54.110 --> 00:11:57.650
that maybe they didn't have
or things they needed to do,

00:11:57.650 --> 00:12:00.290
and he was determined to
do those kinds of things

00:12:00.290 --> 00:12:03.710
that needed to be done,
to help with his mission.

00:12:03.710 --> 00:12:10.750
So he returned in late, in early
2004, from Iraq, and was chosen

00:12:10.750 --> 00:12:14.610
to be an Aid to General Ben
Allen at Fort Hood, Texas.

00:12:14.610 --> 00:12:17.790
And unfortunately the
money after Thanksgiving,

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:19.390
there were seven
on a helicopter,

00:12:19.390 --> 00:12:23.290
including General Allen and
Colonel Jim Moore and they were,

00:12:23.290 --> 00:12:26.100
they hit a communication
tower outside of Fort Hood

00:12:26.100 --> 00:12:28.700
in heavy fog, and all perished.

00:12:28.700 --> 00:12:33.590
But we were blessed to have a
close relationship with our son.

00:12:33.590 --> 00:12:35.450
And he loved his job.

00:12:35.450 --> 00:12:39.020
He told me every day when
he got up to go to work,

00:12:39.020 --> 00:12:41.340
he loved what he was doing.

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:42.810
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Thank you Becky.

00:12:42.810 --> 00:12:44.700
General William Caldwell,

00:12:44.700 --> 00:12:49.340
to mention where General
Caldwell has been during a long

00:12:49.340 --> 00:12:53.200
and illustrious career in the US
military would take probably the

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:55.560
rest of this afternoon
and we'd have

00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:59.610
to serve drinks this
evening and just continue,

00:12:59.610 --> 00:13:02.120
not a bad idea by the way.

00:13:02.120 --> 00:13:06.300
Currently he is the President of
Georgia Military Prep College.

00:13:06.300 --> 00:13:08.180
He has helped facilitate
the awarding

00:13:08.180 --> 00:13:13.150
of New Day USA scholarships to
children of Gold Star families

00:13:13.150 --> 00:13:15.970
and children of disabled
veterans.

00:13:15.970 --> 00:13:21.440
General how important is it for
a family to learn as so many

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:22.740
of your students have learned

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:26.530
from having received
scholarships from New Day USA,

00:13:26.530 --> 00:13:30.390
how it, important is it for them
to know that there are people

00:13:30.390 --> 00:13:33.130
out there that they don't
even know who really care

00:13:33.130 --> 00:13:35.450
about who they are and
what they've been through?

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:38.220
&gt;&gt; Lt. Gen. William B.
Caldwell: Well Mort thanks.

00:13:38.220 --> 00:13:41.260
I, I'm glad we didn't go
through my, my history.

00:13:41.260 --> 00:13:43.110
I wasn't sure if you were
just saying that I'm older

00:13:43.110 --> 00:13:44.410
than you or not though.

00:13:44.410 --> 00:13:49.640
I do want to say it really is
important for us to remember.

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:51.780
Everybody up here will tell you

00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:53.690
that we don't want
to ever forget.

00:13:53.690 --> 00:13:57.210
I feel very blessed today that
I've been able to be a part

00:13:57.210 --> 00:14:01.160
of a life of the young
lady there, Carolyn Wood,

00:14:01.160 --> 00:14:05.270
who lost her father,
and she's at our school.

00:14:05.270 --> 00:14:06.760
She's attending there.

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:08.060
We've got some other kids

00:14:08.060 --> 00:14:11.650
who are also Gold Star family
children that are at our school,

00:14:11.650 --> 00:14:15.770
and we're incredibly blessed in
our ability to remember them,

00:14:15.770 --> 00:14:18.710
that we hold a ceremony
every 9-11 and during

00:14:18.710 --> 00:14:21.380
that ceremony we lay a wreath.

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:25.170
And it's done in remembrance of
those who lost their fathers,

00:14:25.170 --> 00:14:27.380
mothers, brothers, sisters.

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:30.920
In our case its two fathers
and four young children

00:14:30.920 --> 00:14:33.770
that are there that we go out
and do this lay the wreath.

00:14:33.770 --> 00:14:36.600
We're in military uniforms
at this preparatory school,

00:14:36.600 --> 00:14:38.550
the fourth through 12th grade.

00:14:38.550 --> 00:14:42.700
But what makes it really
special today for us is the fact

00:14:42.700 --> 00:14:44.660
that New Day stepped forward.

00:14:44.660 --> 00:14:47.520
Rob Posner stepped
forward and said I,

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:50.160
I want to help these
families and I know

00:14:50.160 --> 00:14:52.450
that you charge a
tuition to go there.

00:14:52.450 --> 00:14:54.290
It's like a charter school.

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:58.440
And I want to relieve
their parents, their mother

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:00.390
or their father,
whomever is raising them

00:15:00.390 --> 00:15:04.080
of all financial burden
to attend that school.

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:06.780
And we've been just
enormously blessed,

00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:08.350
and that he's now
been doing that.

00:15:08.350 --> 00:15:09.980
His company has, New Day has.

00:15:09.980 --> 00:15:13.940
And it makes an enormous
difference on those families

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:17.090
when there are other
Americans who recognize

00:15:17.090 --> 00:15:21.290
that the sacrifice is enduring,
it's not a one-time sacrifice,

00:15:21.290 --> 00:15:24.920
it's a, it's a life
commitment that somebody made

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:27.490
to our nation for others.

00:15:27.490 --> 00:15:30.400
And the fact that
New Day has done

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:32.140
that is making a
remarkable difference

00:15:32.140 --> 00:15:35.440
in our little community there
in Milledgeville, Georgia.

00:15:35.440 --> 00:15:38.060
At that ceremony I'll share.

00:15:38.060 --> 00:15:40.800
We just started a fourth
and fifth grade this year.

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:43.450
We added on to this
preparatory school we have.

00:15:43.450 --> 00:15:45.880
And it's all day
students, about 700.

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:49.590
And I was chatting with some of
the fourth graders last week.

00:15:49.590 --> 00:15:51.780
And I asked them, I said what's
the one thing you've really

00:15:51.780 --> 00:15:55.890
enjoyed so far being a part
of this preparatory school.

00:15:55.890 --> 00:15:58.330
This little fourth grade
gal raises her hand.

00:15:58.330 --> 00:16:03.010
She goes, I learned what
it means to do something

00:16:03.010 --> 00:16:06.470
for somebody else
and give your life.

00:16:06.470 --> 00:16:08.810
I've never been taught
that before.

00:16:08.810 --> 00:16:10.110
And I said well what
do you mean?

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:12.820
She goes, well that 9-11
thing that you all did.

00:16:12.820 --> 00:16:16.870
She said, when we came out there
and listened to the stories,

00:16:16.870 --> 00:16:19.960
and heard of people doing
something for somebody else

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:21.510
by giving their life,

00:16:21.510 --> 00:16:25.110
we realized that there are some
great Americans around here.

00:16:25.110 --> 00:16:27.700
And this is coming out of
the mouth of a fourth grader.

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:32.200
And so I just, I, I think
we all, as a nation,

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:34.890
need to constantly remind
ourselves just how blessed we

00:16:34.890 --> 00:16:38.650
are by having men
and women, you know,

00:16:38.650 --> 00:16:41.680
who will serve their
nation like they have

00:16:41.680 --> 00:16:45.510
and to therefore
remember their families

00:16:45.510 --> 00:16:47.440
continuously thereafter.

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:48.740
But anyway, so--

00:16:48.740 --> 00:16:50.040
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Thank you General.

00:16:50.040 --> 00:16:54.020
And while I, I visited the
college and met the General,

00:16:54.020 --> 00:16:55.510
last year I guess it was.

00:16:55.510 --> 00:16:57.740
And not all that long ago.

00:16:57.740 --> 00:17:00.650
And he was dressed in
his full dress uniform.

00:17:00.650 --> 00:17:03.260
And he was walking through
the corridor and I thought,

00:17:03.260 --> 00:17:04.680
oh this is going
to be interesting,

00:17:04.680 --> 00:17:07.320
all of the students are going
to shrink back and they're going

00:17:07.320 --> 00:17:09.570
to be frightened
by his presence.

00:17:09.570 --> 00:17:13.070
But it was just the opposite.

00:17:13.070 --> 00:17:17.410
And it just struck me that
given the proper introduction

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:23.110
to people in uniform, being
told what the uniform means,

00:17:23.110 --> 00:17:27.140
really does change their--
the attitude of young people

00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:30.670
so that they respect people
in uniform, and they think

00:17:30.670 --> 00:17:36.130
of them not as some obscure
people, but as friends,

00:17:36.130 --> 00:17:40.990
people who care about them
and they in turn end up caring

00:17:40.990 --> 00:17:42.570
about people like yourself.

00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:47.620
Bonnie Carroll, a veteran,
Founder and President of TAPS,

00:17:47.620 --> 00:17:50.750
Tragedy Assistance
Programs for Survivors.

00:17:50.750 --> 00:17:53.870
Recipient of the
Presidential Medal of Freedom,

00:17:53.870 --> 00:17:57.650
which is not-- it's a big deal.

00:17:57.650 --> 00:18:00.430
A Gold Star spouse.

00:18:00.430 --> 00:18:03.220
Tell us a little bit about TAPS.

00:18:03.220 --> 00:18:07.340
&gt;&gt; Bonnie Carroll: Well in
1992 my husband was killed

00:18:07.340 --> 00:18:10.970
in an army plane crash along
with seven other soldiers.

00:18:10.970 --> 00:18:16.290
And like Becky, and her son,
my husband was a combat veteran

00:18:16.290 --> 00:18:19.070
and a recipient of the Bronze
Star and the Air Medal.

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:20.740
We certainly did not expect

00:18:20.740 --> 00:18:22.990
that his career would
end in that way.

00:18:22.990 --> 00:18:25.310
So I immediately went looking
for the kind of the support

00:18:25.310 --> 00:18:27.320
that I knew had to
exist for other types

00:18:27.320 --> 00:18:29.230
of loss of our society.

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:32.170
Immediately became a life
member of Gold Star Wives.

00:18:32.170 --> 00:18:35.290
And worked with the
Department of Veterans Affairs,

00:18:35.290 --> 00:18:40.440
the Department of Defense to
identify any gaps that existed.

00:18:40.440 --> 00:18:44.380
The support that I found in
Gold Star Wives and talking

00:18:44.380 --> 00:18:46.890
with other organizations
was fantastic,

00:18:46.890 --> 00:18:51.770
but what was most valuable
was the peer connection,

00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:55.310
being with others
who truly understood

00:18:55.310 --> 00:18:57.890
in a very personal way
because they were also walking

00:18:57.890 --> 00:18:59.940
this journey.

00:18:59.940 --> 00:19:04.160
Back in the early '90s there was
no organization in partnership

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:06.020
with Gold Star Wives,
Gold Star Mothers,

00:19:06.020 --> 00:19:09.710
Society of Military Widows
to address some of the nuts

00:19:09.710 --> 00:19:13.010
and bolts, the casework
assistance,

00:19:13.010 --> 00:19:16.830
the peer based emotional
support and grief counseling.

00:19:16.830 --> 00:19:20.230
A 24/7 help line that
could be maintained

00:19:20.230 --> 00:19:22.390
by trained peer mentors.

00:19:22.390 --> 00:19:23.690
Connections to free

00:19:23.690 --> 00:19:25.750
and unlimited clinical
grief counseling,

00:19:25.750 --> 00:19:28.680
if additional support
was required.

00:19:28.680 --> 00:19:34.510
So in 1994, TAPS was launched
and immediately was embraced

00:19:34.510 --> 00:19:37.610
by the Defense Department
as a wonderful compliment

00:19:37.610 --> 00:19:40.880
to the other organizations and
to what the government could do.

00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:43.960
Today General Dempsey, former
Chairman of the Joint Chiefs,

00:19:43.960 --> 00:19:45.260
is on our Board of Directors.

00:19:45.260 --> 00:19:46.840
And he puts it beautifully.

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:49.540
He says, the government
does a magnificent job

00:19:49.540 --> 00:19:52.040
of administering benefit's,

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:56.070
and rendering final
honors when a death occurs.

00:19:56.070 --> 00:19:59.020
We honor all those who
have given their lives

00:19:59.020 --> 00:20:00.320
for this country.

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:04.050
But what we can't do in
the military is be there

00:20:04.050 --> 00:20:05.850
for the emotional support,

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:08.800
for the additional financial
assistance, for the connections

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:10.730
to the educational
benefits that are offered

00:20:10.730 --> 00:20:16.500
in the private sector, for the
24/7 resource that is given

00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:19.960
by peers who truly understand.

00:20:19.960 --> 00:20:23.680
So we've had the support
since the very early days

00:20:23.680 --> 00:20:26.870
of every chairman who has
directed the families,

00:20:26.870 --> 00:20:30.280
or referred and connected to
the support that TAPS can offer.

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:33.230
And it is a family,
it's a family of all

00:20:33.230 --> 00:20:38.820
of us Gold Star Wives, Gold
Star mothers, siblings, dads,

00:20:38.820 --> 00:20:42.620
together on this
journey honoring those

00:20:42.620 --> 00:20:45.440
who have served and died.

00:20:45.440 --> 00:20:46.740
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Thank you.

00:20:46.740 --> 00:20:48.040
And I hope we'll all
participate later

00:20:48.040 --> 00:20:55.490
on in discussing what more we
can all do to show that we care

00:20:55.490 --> 00:20:59.140
and how we, what we can
do to energize others,

00:20:59.140 --> 00:21:01.550
especially people in
the halls of Congress,

00:21:01.550 --> 00:21:04.560
and in official Washington
to realize

00:21:04.560 --> 00:21:07.980
that they do have a
lot more to accomplish.

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:10.280
Dale Egan is Vice President

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:14.060
of the Hershel Woody
Williams Foundation.

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:17.910
And their memorials are all

00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:19.820
around the country
honoring those

00:21:19.820 --> 00:21:22.050
who have given their
lives to our country.

00:21:22.050 --> 00:21:25.560
You've, you've erected
many, many memorials

00:21:25.560 --> 00:21:29.380
around the country, what purpose
do you think they really serve?

00:21:29.380 --> 00:21:30.680
&gt;&gt; Chad Graham: That's
a good question.

00:21:30.680 --> 00:21:31.980
I subbed out Dale today.

00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:33.640
Dale wasn't able
to make it, so I--

00:21:33.640 --> 00:21:34.940
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Oh--

00:21:34.940 --> 00:21:36.240
&gt;&gt; Chad Graham: I'm
Chad, Chad Graham,

00:21:36.240 --> 00:21:37.540
President of Hershel Woody
Williams Foundation--

00:21:37.540 --> 00:21:38.840
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: No, nobody--

00:21:38.840 --> 00:21:40.140
&gt;&gt; Chad Graham: You
expected Dale,

00:21:40.140 --> 00:21:41.440
but you didn't get him, so--

00:21:41.440 --> 00:21:42.810
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: And I'm
not really Mort Dean,

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:47.500
I am just-- I'm just--

00:21:47.500 --> 00:21:49.290
&gt;&gt; Chad Graham: No that's fine,
I just didn't want them to think

00:21:49.290 --> 00:21:50.990
that Dale was this
ugly, so you know.

00:21:50.990 --> 00:21:57.770
No but I am, I am, I am honored
to be here and, and that's,

00:21:57.770 --> 00:21:59.070
that's a great question.

00:21:59.070 --> 00:22:03.920
And I think the best answer that
I can offer is what I've heard

00:22:03.920 --> 00:22:06.430
from these Gold Star families
that are sitting up here,

00:22:06.430 --> 00:22:08.570
and the Gold Star
families that are out here.

00:22:08.570 --> 00:22:12.750
And, and that sacrifice, and
what that monument means.

00:22:12.750 --> 00:22:17.250
In terms of, of going into these
communities, so many communities

00:22:17.250 --> 00:22:19.480
as you started out with, they,

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:21.750
they don't know what
a Gold Star family is.

00:22:21.750 --> 00:22:25.320
And we have a duty, as
you said, to, to everyone

00:22:25.320 --> 00:22:26.620
and the general public.

00:22:26.620 --> 00:22:30.390
We need to lead this movement
to put that on the forefront.

00:22:30.390 --> 00:22:33.010
And within our communities,
every community needs to realize

00:22:33.010 --> 00:22:35.190
that there are Gold Star
families living amongst them.

00:22:35.190 --> 00:22:37.860
And that the reason they
can have the community,

00:22:37.860 --> 00:22:39.970
and the reason that we can live
the lives that we've had is

00:22:39.970 --> 00:22:42.240
because somebody else laid
down their life for it and paid

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:43.920
that ultimate sacrifice.

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:47.520
And what our hope is that
these monuments act as a way,

00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:50.060
a gathering place for that,
something that can serve

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:53.170
as a launch pad for Gold Star
mothers, Gold Star wives,

00:22:53.170 --> 00:22:56.140
Gold Star siblings, Gold Star
children for all those folks

00:22:56.140 --> 00:22:59.350
to gather, because it is
for them, and it is theirs

00:22:59.350 --> 00:23:01.170
to use as they see fit.

00:23:01.170 --> 00:23:04.140
And from the public side
they, they get an education

00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:07.300
about what, what is a Gold Star
family, and what does that mean

00:23:07.300 --> 00:23:09.440
and hopefully that, that grows.

00:23:09.440 --> 00:23:12.340
And we can be a small part of
that and be a catalyst for that.

00:23:12.340 --> 00:23:15.160
And our hope is that each
one of these monuments now

00:23:15.160 --> 00:23:18.270
that we have 40 by the end of
the year we'll have about 50

00:23:18.270 --> 00:23:20.680
that have been established
across the United States,

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:23.760
that those serve as,
as a starting point.

00:23:23.760 --> 00:23:26.680
Those monuments are
there as a way that,

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:28.980
that we can gather
these Gold Star families

00:23:28.980 --> 00:23:31.460
and also keep it fresh
on the communities mind,

00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:34.560
because as we've all heard,
it is so, so important for us

00:23:34.560 --> 00:23:38.670
to say every day, those loved
ones names who have fallen.

00:23:38.670 --> 00:23:40.660
And the only way we can keep
that in the public eye is

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:42.930
to have something
that is permanent,

00:23:42.930 --> 00:23:45.610
and something there
that's in the public view.

00:23:45.610 --> 00:23:46.910
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: That's good.

00:23:46.910 --> 00:23:49.630
So whatever your name really is,

00:23:49.630 --> 00:23:53.440
but why did you get
involved in, in this project?

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:57.080
&gt;&gt; Chad Graham: Our family
kind of came together in 2010.

00:23:57.080 --> 00:23:59.800
We were getting to, to
celebrate our fifth birthday

00:23:59.800 --> 00:24:01.360
as an organization.

00:24:01.360 --> 00:24:06.880
But about 2010, and we're really
talking about the, the influence

00:24:06.880 --> 00:24:08.580
of my grandfather,
Woody Williams, who,

00:24:08.580 --> 00:24:11.130
whose the namesake
of, of the foundation.

00:24:11.130 --> 00:24:12.990
At a young age, when he tried

00:24:12.990 --> 00:24:14.290
to enter the Marine
Corps he was turned

00:24:14.290 --> 00:24:15.870
down because they had
a height requirement

00:24:15.870 --> 00:24:18.840
that he did not fit at the time.

00:24:18.840 --> 00:24:21.500
His, in the interim between them
lowering the height requirement.

00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:25.060
He was actually delivering
Western Union telegrams

00:24:25.060 --> 00:24:27.920
to families, that was
a notice of death.

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:31.870
And my grandfather, that had
such a huge impact on him.

00:24:31.870 --> 00:24:35.310
And I remember from the time
I was a little guy we used

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:36.610
to show horses together.

00:24:36.610 --> 00:24:37.910
And we'd be riding
around the countryside

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:39.210
and he would tell
me these stories.

00:24:39.210 --> 00:24:40.960
Because it was always
something that he taught us.

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:44.200
He taught us that leadership
is service, and that service

00:24:44.200 --> 00:24:46.890
above self there is nothing
more righteous on this planet

00:24:46.890 --> 00:24:48.490
that any of us can do.

00:24:48.490 --> 00:24:51.430
And that was always a part
of the fabric of our family.

00:24:51.430 --> 00:24:53.980
When we started talking about
formalizing a foundation,

00:24:53.980 --> 00:24:56.550
none of us had any idea.

00:24:56.550 --> 00:24:59.360
We definitely didn't,
didn't have the funding

00:24:59.360 --> 00:25:00.660
to start a foundation.

00:25:00.660 --> 00:25:02.680
We didn't really
have that direction.

00:25:02.680 --> 00:25:05.020
I think divine intervention
had a hand in it,

00:25:05.020 --> 00:25:08.310
and I think the biggest thing
is, is our, our duty is,

00:25:08.310 --> 00:25:09.640
is to do what we're doing.

00:25:09.640 --> 00:25:14.440
And so for me, as, as a family
member, outside of that a,

00:25:14.440 --> 00:25:15.740
a few years back when we,

00:25:15.740 --> 00:25:19.450
we really started
formalizing the organization,

00:25:19.450 --> 00:25:24.090
I saw it personally as, as
something of a calling to me.

00:25:24.090 --> 00:25:26.900
It's part of my personal mission
and, and it's very important

00:25:26.900 --> 00:25:28.260
to all of us in the
organization.

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:30.310
I think we're very,
very fortunate

00:25:30.310 --> 00:25:32.600
that everybody involved shares

00:25:32.600 --> 00:25:35.050
in that personal
commitment to our mission.

00:25:35.050 --> 00:25:36.350
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Good, good.

00:25:36.350 --> 00:25:37.650
Thank you.

00:25:37.650 --> 00:25:40.130
And I know some of you have some
questions and some comments,

00:25:40.130 --> 00:25:44.570
and I hope you all participate,
just raise your hand

00:25:44.570 --> 00:25:46.210
and we'll be able to hear you.

00:25:46.210 --> 00:25:49.690
If not, a microphone
will be at your side.

