For the last two years
we have had a major focus

00:36:40.910 --> 00:36:45.200
on military suicide
awareness because this is one

00:36:45.200 --> 00:36:50.420
of those unspoken sort of
hidden in the back issues

00:36:50.420 --> 00:36:57.210
that I think we as Americans
have overlooked for a long time.

00:36:57.210 --> 00:37:00.790
And so we started that
program last year,

00:37:00.790 --> 00:37:03.780
and we have done quite
a lot to raise money

00:37:03.780 --> 00:37:06.850
for Working Dogs for
Vets, especially.

00:37:06.850 --> 00:37:09.240
And so we've continued
that mission this year.

00:37:09.240 --> 00:37:14.510
And that mission is, is
going to go on because this,

00:37:14.510 --> 00:37:17.600
this is a serious,
serious issue.

00:37:17.600 --> 00:37:21.860
Sometimes it's years after
one of our service men

00:37:21.860 --> 00:37:24.330
or women have left the service

00:37:24.330 --> 00:37:28.420
and years later they
die by suicide.

00:37:28.420 --> 00:37:31.420
So there are many programs,
many things that are out there

00:37:31.420 --> 00:37:35.590
but we need to make people aware
of those, they need support.

00:37:35.590 --> 00:37:40.530
And as I said, we have worked
with Working Dogs for Vets,

00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:43.660
which is based in Tennessee
for the last two years.

00:37:43.660 --> 00:37:47.080
They've been quite successful
with service dogs for those

00:37:47.080 --> 00:37:51.770
who have those tendencies,
suffer from TBI or PSD.

00:37:51.770 --> 00:37:57.320
And so we are really focused on
this, and we are very serious

00:37:57.320 --> 00:38:02.170
about this, and we are trying
to make every American aware

00:38:02.170 --> 00:38:04.570
to help with this issue.

00:38:05.850 --> 00:38:09.750
&gt;&gt; Mort Dean: Tell me if, if
you've had this experience.

00:38:09.750 --> 00:38:13.810
I, I think you probably
have had.

00:38:13.810 --> 00:38:17.300
But in, in prepping
for this documentary

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:20.340
and a few other things that
I've, I've been working on,

00:38:20.340 --> 00:38:23.450
I have found that often
when you go to a veteran,

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:26.290
or you make a cold call,
somebody you know who has been

00:38:26.290 --> 00:38:29.870
in the service, and you say
look I'm working on something,

00:38:29.870 --> 00:38:32.160
I want to talk to you
about your service.

00:38:32.160 --> 00:38:34.770
It's usually, well
thank you very much,

00:38:34.770 --> 00:38:39.230
but I'm not interested, I, I
wish you good luck with it.

00:38:39.230 --> 00:38:42.430
And I have found that,
that just saying thank you

00:38:42.430 --> 00:38:45.710
for your service which to some
people is [inaudible] now,

00:38:45.710 --> 00:38:47.190
is not enough.

00:38:47.190 --> 00:38:52.670
That as a good friend of mine
who did duty in Vietnam has said

00:38:52.670 --> 00:38:55.040
to crowds, said,
what we really want

00:38:55.040 --> 00:38:56.940
to know is that you love us.

00:38:56.940 --> 00:38:59.570
That you really care about us.

00:38:59.570 --> 00:39:02.280
Anybody can say thank
you, but you know,

00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:05.010
ask me what's really going on.

00:39:05.010 --> 00:39:08.960
And it's been amazing to me
how many people have responded

00:39:08.960 --> 00:39:14.190
to that, and have said, well
call me back we'll talk.

00:39:14.190 --> 00:39:17.900
And you know we've made a
number of friends simply

00:39:17.900 --> 00:39:21.010
by proving that we care.

00:39:21.010 --> 00:39:23.530
Does that make sense
to you General?

00:39:24.800 --> 00:39:26.260
&gt;&gt; Lt. Gen. William B. Caldwell:
I, I think it really does.

00:39:26.260 --> 00:39:31.040
I remember the first time we
did the welcome home ceremony

00:39:31.040 --> 00:39:35.410
for our Vietnam veterans back
in 2000, it was right around 13

00:39:35.410 --> 00:39:38.120
at Fort Sam Houston, Texas.

00:39:38.120 --> 00:39:42.270
And it was one of the first in
the nation that the veterans,

00:39:42.270 --> 00:39:45.690
you know, group had
started talking about doing

00:39:45.690 --> 00:39:46.990
through the Department
of Defense.

00:39:46.990 --> 00:39:49.620
And we signed up and
said we'd love to do it.

00:39:49.620 --> 00:39:51.680
And I can tell you it
wasn't the ceremony itself,

00:39:51.680 --> 00:39:54.870
it was the aftermath, it
was the reception area,

00:39:54.870 --> 00:39:58.310
inside the quadrangle that you
saw the emotions just running

00:39:58.310 --> 00:40:01.270
tremendously high with
everybody hugging each other.

00:40:01.270 --> 00:40:05.470
And young people, young soldiers
that were there going up

00:40:05.470 --> 00:40:07.470
and hugging these
veterans and telling them,

00:40:07.470 --> 00:40:09.280
thank you for what
you did during a time

00:40:09.280 --> 00:40:11.830
when our nation really
was not very grateful

00:40:11.830 --> 00:40:14.540
for your willingness to
sacrifice for others.

00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:17.550
And gosh it was, it
was a moving ceremony.

00:40:17.550 --> 00:40:20.730
I remember Joe [inaudible] came
out for it and he was there,

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:24.980
he was heading up that group
and it, it does if you,

00:40:24.980 --> 00:40:28.550
if you spend the time to
really tell them how much,

00:40:28.550 --> 00:40:32.480
it's not just the thank you for
what you did, but truly we, we,

00:40:32.480 --> 00:40:38.200
we can feel it deep inside the
realization that you were ready

00:40:38.200 --> 00:40:42.000
to make that sacrifice that
had been required, and,

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:43.900
and you're home now and
we just need to know

00:40:43.900 --> 00:40:47.200
that we really do appreciate
it, appreciate them.

